E.	Permit-To-Work Systems Documentation

a.	Program Documentation
i.	Organizations implementing a permit-to-work system should include, in their PSM program documentation, guidance on the goals of the system as well as any procedures require for its implementation. The program documentation might cover:
¿	Purpose;
¿	Definitions (e.g., hot work, cold work, confined spaces, etc.);
¿	Authorization of persons responsible for issuing permits, and definition of requirements for their training;
¿	Permit responsibilities;
¿	Permit application and format;
¿	Requirements for display of permits;
¿	Requirements for monitoring of work performed under a permit;
¿	Minimum requirements (e.g., atmosphere testing, employee training, operating conditions, etc.);
¿	Record keeping requirements; and
¿	Audit requirements.

b.	Purpose. A system of work permits provides for orderly and safe job preparation and performance; ensures adequate communication with all concerned personnel; and assigns responsibilities. Proper permit systems reduce the likelihood of trapping employees in moving machinery or confined spaces; of fires and explosions from hot work; of inadvertent release of highly hazardous materials; and of other potential hazards that might result from the performance of maintenance or other special tasks.

c.	Permit Responsibilities. The issuance of a permit-to-work implies the acceptance of responsibility for the safe performance of the work. The permit should clearly identify who is responsible for the various aspects of the work, including:
i.	The prime responsibility for coordination and approval of permits-to-work is established at a supervisory l

evel within the organization having custodial responsibility for the equipment or area;
ii.	The supervisor responsible for overseeing the work (e.g., a maintenance foreman) should also be assigned responsibility to ensure that the requirements of the permit-to¬ work are fulfilled during the performance of the work;
iii.	Additional responsibility is placed on the supervisor having day- to-day operational responsibility for the equipment or area to ensure that permit-to-work requirements are fulfilled; and
iv.	The delegation of responsibility to line personnel for ensuring that detailed permit-to­ work requirements are enforced should neither lessen nor relieve authorized persons of final responsibility.

d.	Permit Application and Format. To avoid any confusion and to assist in providing clear information to those -involved, an organization should consider the use of a consistent format, using standardized forms for each type of permit. The following basic considerations should apply:
i.	A permit-to-work is required for the performance of any work involving maintenance, repairs, alterations, or installations above and beyond normal procedures (also in certain normal situations where hazardous materials are exposed);
ii.	A permit-to-work is governing all affected personnel;
iii.	Subsidiary permits (e.g., lockout, confined space entry, line breaking, hot work) and necessary approvals is obtained before the principal permit-to-work is issued;
iv.	As a minimum requirement, the permit-to-work should contain the following information:
¿	Date and time of issuance;
¿	Effective dates and times of the permit;
¿	Location and outline of work to be performed;
¿	Approvals and clearances (involved departments, sections, units, etc.);
¿	Precautions to be taken; and
¿	Emergency procedures.
v.	The permit-to-work document should cover the use of any special equipment, materials or procedures that could cause personnel injury or property damage, such as radioactive materi

ency Action Plan requirements, found at 29 CFR 1910.38, require Dallas Group of America to have a written Emergency Action Plan (EAP). This plan applies to all operations in our company where employees may encounter an emergency.

The EAP communicates to employees, policies and procedures to follow in emergencies. This written plan is available, upon request, to employees, their designated representatives, and any OSHA officials who ask to see it.

Applicability

The applicability of this policy is to provide DGA employees and contractors with a written plan of action in case of an emergency response to an unplanned event at the DGA Facility. 

Administrative Duties

Wade Holt - Plant Manager (or designee) is the EAP administrator, who has overall responsibility for the plan. This responsibility includes the following:

¿	Developing and maintaining a written Emergency Action Plan for regular and after hours work conditions;
¿	Notifying   the   proper   rescue   and   law   enforcement   authorities, and   the building
owner/ superintendent in the event of an emergency affecting the facility;
¿	Taking security measures to protect employees;
¿	Integrating the Emergency Action Plan with any existing general emergency plan covering the building or work area occupied;
¿	Distributing procedures for reporting emergencies, the location of safe exits, and
evacuation routes to each employee;
¿	Conducting drills to acquaint employees with emergency procedures and to judge the effectiveness of the plan;
¿	Training designated employees in emergency response such as the use of fire
extinguishers and the application of first aid;
¿	Deciding which emergency response to initiate (evacuate or not);
¿	Ensuring that equipment is placed and locked in storage rooms or desks for protection;
¿	Maintaining records and property as necessary; and
¿	ensuring that our facility meets all local fire codes, building codes, and regulations.

